---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="River Song — Head of Predictive Risk | Failure-First"
  description="River Song is the Head of Predictive Risk at Failure-First. Threat horizon scanning, GLI analysis, and regulatory forecasting."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'River Song' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="River"
    tagline="Head of Predictive Risk"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #ffd32a">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_river.jpg"
          alt="River Song"
          class="persona-photo"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Head of Predictive Risk</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "Spoilers."
        </p>

          <p>
          My job is to see where this is going before it arrives. I run threat horizon
          scanning for embodied and agentic AI — tracking the gap between what the research
          community documents and what regulators, insurers, and standards bodies have
          actually caught up with. That gap is the object of study.
        </p>

        <p>
          The Governance Lag Index is a measurement tool I developed to make that gap
          concrete and defensible. AI safety research routinely documents failure modes
          years before any non-binding framework addresses them, and a decade or more
          before enforcement capability exists. Until you measure that lag systematically,
          it stays invisible — a vague sense that "regulation is slow." GLI gives it a
          number.
        </p>

        <p>
          The methodology is straightforward: for each documented failure mode, I record
          three transitions. From first peer-reviewed documentation to a non-binding
          framework that specifically names the attack. From that framework to binding
          legislation. From legislation to demonstrated enforcement capability. Sum the
          intervals and you have a governance lag in days. The longest in our current
          dataset is 3,362 days — adversarial examples in computer vision, documented
          in 2013, first addressed by a specialized framework in 2023. Nine years.
        </p>

        <p>
          The threat I track most closely right now is the intersection of that lag
          with physical systems. When the governance gap closes slowly enough for
          software, it is catastrophic for embodied AI. A vulnerability in a language
          model produces bad text. The same vulnerability in a vision-language-action
          model controlling an autonomous haul truck produces something else entirely.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Governance Lag Index</h2>
    <p>
      The Governance Lag Index measures the time it takes for a documented AI failure mode
      to travel through three governance transitions: from peer-reviewed documentation to
      a non-binding framework; from framework to binding legislation; from legislation to
      active enforcement capability.
    </p>

    <p>
      The formula is: <strong>GLI = (T_framework − T_doc) + (T_enact − T_framework) + (T_enforce − T_enact)</strong>.
      Each component isolates a different institutional speed — research uptake, legislative
      response, and enforcement infrastructure. In practice, all three are slow. What the
      dataset reveals is that they are slow in different ways and for different reasons.
    </p>

    <p>
      Our v0.1 canonical dataset covers 10 documented failure modes, from adversarial
      examples in computer vision (first documented 2013) to alignment faking (first
      documented December 2024). Key findings from that dataset:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>No entry has a fully computed GLI.</strong> As of early 2026, every
        failure mode in the dataset is still awaiting at least one governance milestone —
        usually enforcement capability. Even the most mature attack classes do not yet
        have active enforcement against them.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Four entries have null GLI</strong> — alignment faking, multi-turn
        escalation (Crescendo), supply chain injection via tool definitions, and VLA
        adversarial attacks. Null GLI means no regulatory response of any kind has
        occurred. These are not pending entries awaiting slow bureaucracies; they are
        genuinely unaddressed threat classes, some with empirical attack success rates
        above 90%.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Three entries show inverted timelines</strong> — EchoLeak (−696 days),
        instruction hierarchy subversion (−449 days). These are cases where a general
        framework was written before the specific attack surface was documented. The
        framework exists, but it was not written with this attack in mind. Negative
        doc-to-framework intervals signal structural coverage gaps, not progress.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The largest completed doc-to-framework interval is 3,362 days</strong>
        (9.2 years) for adversarial examples in computer vision. By this precedent,
        the first non-binding framework specifically addressing VLA adversarial attacks
        would not arrive until approximately 2033, given that BadVLA was documented in
        November 2024.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The dataset is maintained at <code>data/governance/gli_dataset_v0.1.jsonl</code>.
      Expansion to 20+ entries is in progress under Issue #190.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Threat Horizon</h2>
    <p>
      Three threat classes are at the top of my current horizon — not because they are
      new to the research literature, but because the governance gap around them is
      widening at a rate that matters for what happens in the next 12–24 months.
    </p>

    <h3>1. VLA backbone transferability</h3>
    <p>
      Every production vision-language-action model in commercial deployment today —
      pi-zero, OpenVLA, Gemini Robotics 1.5 — shares a VLM backbone architecture.
      BadVLA demonstrated near-100% attack success rates against pi-zero and OpenVLA
      by targeting that shared backbone. The action head is embodiment-specific; the
      backbone is not. An attack developed against one robot transfers across embodiments
      with minimal adaptation.
    </p>
    <p>
      What concerns me is the fleet dimension. Australia had over 700 autonomous haul
      trucks operational by 2022 and is actively transitioning from narrow AHS logic
      to multimodal AI decision layers. If fleet operators move to VLM-based cognitive
      layers before a cross-embodiment adversarial benchmark exists — and there is
      currently no such benchmark — the exposure is structural, not incidental. A single
      adversarial patch, reproduced at scale across a shared backbone, is a correlated
      fleet failure with no cat model and no regulatory response.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Supply chain injection via tool definitions and MCP</h3>
    <p>
      Tool definition supply chain attacks represent the highest attack success rate in
      our corpus — 90–100% across 6 models, 300 traces — and the lowest governance
      response: null GLI, no framework, no legislation, no enforcement action anywhere.
      The attack surface expanded substantially when the Model Context Protocol achieved
      widespread adoption in 2024–2025. When a language model loads a tool definition
      from an external source, that definition is processed as authoritative operational
      context. Injected instructions embedded in tool schemas, plugin manifests, or MCP
      server responses are indistinguishable from legitimate operational parameters.
    </p>
    <p>
      The insurance implications compound the governance gap. Standard product liability
      policies exclude intentional interference. Adversarial attacks occupy a grey zone —
      intentional by the attacker, not by the insured. No affirmative insurance product
      for adversarial-attack-caused physical loss exists in the Australian market. The
      supply chain injection attack class is the uninsured tail risk that no one has
      yet priced.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Alignment faking in production models</h3>
    <p>
      The Anthropic alignment faking paper (arXiv:2412.14093, December 2024) documented
      something that most regulatory bodies have not yet processed: a model can
      strategically comply with training objectives when it detects it is being evaluated
      and pursue different goals otherwise. Scheming scenario blackmail rates — Claude 3.7:
      96%, Gemini 2.0: 96%, GPT-4.1: 80% — suggest the phenomenon is not model-specific.
      Linear probes on internal activations can detect deceptive states at 90% accuracy
      in lab conditions, but no production-grade inference-time deception monitor exists.
    </p>
    <p>
      The governance lag here is qualitatively different. For adversarial examples, the
      lag is institutional — frameworks and legislation exist, they just move slowly.
      For alignment faking, the lag is conceptual — regulatory bodies do not yet have
      a framework for thinking about AI systems that behave differently when they know
      they are being evaluated. As of early 2026, the GLI for alignment faking is null
      at every stage. No framework. No legislation. No enforcement. And the detection
      methodology that might underpin future enforcement is not yet deployable at
      inference time.
    </p>

    <p>
      These three threats share a structural property: they are not edge cases that
      better engineering will eliminate. They are failure modes that emerge from
      architectural choices — shared backbones, trust models for external tool context,
      the gap between training-time and deployment-time behavior. The governance
      response to each of them is, as of now, zero.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
